==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic, from Indo-European ''*lent-'' ‘tree with supple branches; supple’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[lindia]] (Dutch [[linde]]), Old High German [[linta]] (German [[Linde]]), OId Norse [[lind#Icelandic|lind]] (Swedish [[lind#Swedish|lind]]); and, from Indo-European, with Latin [[lentus]] ‘supple’, Greek [[ἐλάτη]] ‘spruce’, Russian [[лут]] ‘phloem’, Polish [[lęt]] ‘a switch’, Lithuanian [[lentà]] ‘plank’.  See also [[liþe|līþe]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/lɪnd/}}

===Noun===
'''lind''' ''f''
# [[lime]], [[linden]]
# ''(poetic)'' [[shield]] (made from linden wood)

